  "bib_entries": {
    "9863092": {
      "title": "The obesity-cancer link: lessons learned from a fatless mouse",
      "abstract": "Current dogma suggests that the positive correlation between obesity and cancer is driven by white adipose tissue that accompanies obesity, possibly through excess secretion of adipokines. Recent studies in fatless A-Zip/F1 mice, which have undetectable adipokine levels but display accelerated tumor formation, suggest that adipokines are not required for the enhanced tumor development. The A-Zip/F-1 mice are also diabetic and display elevated circulating levels of other factors frequently associated with obesity (insulin, insulin-like growth factor-1, and proinflammatory cytokines) and activation of several signaling pathways associated with carcinogenesis. In view of this information, the risk factors underlying the obesity-cancer link need to be revisited. We postulate that the pathways associated with insulin resistance and inflammation, rather than adipocyte-derived factors, may represent key prevention and therapeutic targets for disrupting the obesity-cancer link."
    },
    "35783658": {
      "title": "Leptin is a growth factor in c\u00e2ncer",
      "abstract": "Obesity has been recognized as an important risk factor for many serious medical conditions. The association of obesity with an increased risk of many cancers is of enormous economic importance to the health industry. The regulation of normal body weight is, in part, orchestrated by the presence of leptin, an adipocyte-derived hormone that acts on the brain to regulate food intake. It is proposed that leptin serves a primary role as an anti-obesity hormone by acting as a signal for the switch between the starved and fed state. Although circulating leptin is thought to control obesity, most obesity occurs in the presence of increased circulating leptin. Leptin exerts effects on metabolism and cardiovascular and renal function, independent of its role in long-term body weight regulation. In addition, we now know that leptin acts as a growth factor on certain organs in both normal and disease states. Therefore, it is plausible, that as a mitogenic agent, leptin acts to promote cancer growth. There is increasing epidemiological data in humans, as well as numerous in vitro investigative reports and animal studies, to suggest a link between leptin and cancer growth. The purposes of this review are as follows: (1) to describe the regulation of leptin production; (2) to propose leptin as a direct physiological agent in cancer growth; and (3) to review the major advances leading to our current understanding of the role of leptin in the pathogenesis of a variety of cancers. THE REGULATION OF LEPTIN PRODUCTION"
    }
  }
}